sentence: Home supply retailer Home Depot ( HD ) will report its second-quarter numbers before the market open August 14.
Analysts forecast earnings of $2.84 per share for the quarter, versus $2.25 during the same period last year.
The stock has appreciated 4.6% on the year.
HD was recently trading at $196.65 down $10.96 from its 12-month high and $49.76 above its 12-month low.
InvestorsObserver's Stock Score Report gives HD an 80 long-term technical score and a 79 short-term technical score.
The stock has recent support above $195 and recent resistance below $203.

Of the 26 analysts who cover the stock 18 rate it Strong Buy, 3 rate it Buy, 5 rate it Hold, 0 rate it Sell , and 0 rate it Strong Sell, HD gets a score of 79 from InvestorsObserver's Stock Score Report.
The housing market remains on solid ground, but with interest rates rising there is some concern over the impact of higher rates on demand.
Even with rates rising this year, interest rates remain incredibly low, it will likely take several more rate hikes before we see a material impact on the housing market.

HD enjoyed a strong bullish run over the last five years, but the stock has been stuck in a sideways trend over the last couple months and has been unable to break through resistance to trade to new highs.

HD trades just below its 52-week high, but its valuation is a little high considering the uncertainties in the housing market, and the company is going to need a solid quarter to push the stock through resistance.
HD has a P/E of 25.7, which is a little high, but earnings have been on the rise, and are expected to rise by 15.2% per annum over the next five years.

The company has managed to post better than expected earnings each of the last seven quarters, so if it can continue that trend earnings growth will be even higher than expected and the stock should move higher as long as we see upside in the overall market.
